01:49.143 --> 01:51.870
I've been here before,

01:51.904 --> 01:54.148
this coastline,

01:54.183 --> 01:56.461
this city.

01:56.495 --> 01:59.188
I was looking
for something then,

01:59.222 --> 02:01.466
but instead I found this.

02:01.500 --> 02:02.000
♪

02:05.746 --> 02:07.196
Uruguay,

02:07.230 --> 02:09.818
the tiny, underappreciated
South American country

02:09.853 --> 02:15.445
tucked between
Argentina and Brazil.

02:15.480 --> 02:17.999
Only 3 million people live here,

02:18.034 --> 02:24.385
half of them in the
capital city of Montevideo.

02:24.420 --> 02:27.043
I love this city.
I love this country.

02:27.077 --> 02:29.735
I mean, there's a vibe here
that just...

02:29.770 --> 02:32.566
It's unlike any other
place on the continent.

02:32.600 --> 02:34.533
It's the opposite of New York
in a lot of ways.

02:34.568 --> 02:36.363
Like, people aren't
pushy here, you know?

02:36.397 --> 02:37.702
In New York,
everybody's, like, sort of

02:37.709 --> 02:39.676
hungry and pushing and moving.

02:39.711 --> 02:41.506
Here it's extremely laid back.

02:41.540 --> 02:43.887
The only competition is soccer.
Well-

02:43.922 --> 02:46.511
- That's the only time
that you get competitive,

02:46.545 --> 02:48.202
and it gets extreme.

02:50.135 --> 02:52.172
Ignacio Mattos is the chef/owner

02:52.206 --> 02:55.830
of three very successful
restaurants in New York City,

02:55.865 --> 02:56.693
Estela,

02:56.728 --> 02:58.488
Cafe Altro Paradiso,

02:58.523 --> 03:00.076
and Flora Bar.

03:00.110 --> 03:02.665
He's been a New Yorker
for the past 12 years,

03:02.699 --> 03:05.012
but he comes from here.

03:05.046 --> 03:08.740
Uruguay is a pretty chill
and relaxed place

03:08.774 --> 03:12.847
where you just can
disconnect from everything.

03:12.882 --> 03:14.746
For me, it's a melting pot.

03:14.780 --> 03:19.060
It's mostly Spanish
and Italian immigrant food.

03:19.095 --> 03:21.235
Bar Arocena in Montevideo's

03:21.270 --> 03:23.237
Carrasco neighborhood
specializes

03:23.272 --> 03:26.206
in Uruguay's unofficial
national sandwich,

03:26.240 --> 03:28.622
the legendary Chivito,

03:28.656 --> 03:29.933
24 hours a day,

03:29.968 --> 03:33.454
seven days a week, since 1923.

03:33.489 --> 03:37.700
A prince, a king,
a Gargantua among sandwiches,

03:37.734 --> 03:40.116
this terror-inspiring
heap of protein

03:40.150 --> 03:44.741
is built out of
steak, ham, bacon, cheese,

03:44.776 --> 03:47.744
hard-boiled egg,
mayo, and garnishes.

03:47.779 --> 03:50.402
That's, like,
a perfect sandwich.

03:50.437 --> 03:52.404
Now, last time I was here,

03:52.439 --> 03:54.579
I have to admit that
after about six days

03:54.613 --> 03:56.719
I would've killed somebody
for a vegetable.

03:56.753 --> 03:58.065
I mean, I didn't see a single...

03:58.099 --> 03:59.599
You're gonna feel
like that very soon.

04:02.034 --> 04:03.415
♪

04:03.450 --> 04:06.004
"Nacho," as he's called
by nearly everyone,

04:06.038 --> 04:08.282
started his career
at the age of 17

04:08.317 --> 04:10.836
with a master of fire
and burning wood,

04:10.871 --> 04:13.287
Argentinean chef
Francis Mallmann,

04:13.322 --> 04:17.118
and stayed with him for ten
years before moving to the U.S.

04:17.153 --> 04:21.088
Working for Francis Mallmann,
I felt at home.

04:21.122 --> 04:23.124
They were just a bunch
of outsiders

04:23.159 --> 04:25.506
that they found a place
where they belonged,

04:25.541 --> 04:29.959
you know, finding this new
culture and, like, new flavors.

04:29.993 --> 04:32.962
♪

04:32.996 --> 04:34.998
- How often do you come?
- Every two years.

04:35.033 --> 04:36.345
And how long do you spend here?

04:36.379 --> 04:39.209
I usually spend a week.

04:39.244 --> 04:42.834
- Why so little?
- We live in New York.

04:42.868 --> 04:44.525
You know what I'm talking about.

04:44.560 --> 04:46.631
- Yeah, I do.
- I mean, I love it here,

04:46.665 --> 04:48.805
but it's... you know,
you have to commit to it here.

04:51.221 --> 04:52.637
But, you know,
you were born here.

04:52.671 --> 04:54.224
You spent your childhood here.

04:54.259 --> 04:55.985
Do you feel the way I feel
about this place?

04:56.019 --> 04:59.678
It... it is special, right?
I-I think it's special.

04:59.713 --> 05:03.510
But I'm so far
detached from it...

05:03.544 --> 05:04.614
Right.

05:04.649 --> 05:06.202
...but I can go back to that,

05:06.236 --> 05:08.825
and I can just connect.

05:08.860 --> 05:10.827
Well, we'll see.
Over the next few days,

05:10.862 --> 05:12.829
we'll see if you can
just slide right back in.

05:12.864 --> 05:15.660
Oh, we will.
Oh, we will.

05:15.694 --> 05:18.007
There's no other way out.
There's no way around it.

05:18.041 --> 05:19.215
You have to.

05:19.249 --> 05:19.749
♪

05:29.743 --> 05:30.243
♪

06:21.450 --> 06:22.451
♪

06:22.485 --> 06:24.418
Things to know about Uruguay.

06:24.453 --> 06:27.732
It's progressive.
Weed is legal.

06:27.766 --> 06:30.044
Abortions are easily accessible.

06:30.079 --> 06:32.322
Gay marriage,
universal healthcare,

06:32.357 --> 06:35.636
free education
including college,

06:35.671 --> 06:38.570
and democracy is no joke here.

06:38.605 --> 06:43.989
96% of eligible Uruguayans
voted in the last election.

06:44.024 --> 06:48.269
Compare that to barely 60%
here in the U.S.

06:48.304 --> 06:50.271
There's something really
special about this place.

06:50.306 --> 06:51.445
You like it?

06:51.480 --> 06:53.102
It's really one of
my favorite countries.

06:53.136 --> 06:55.069
It's really...
Amazing.

06:55.104 --> 06:57.099
Many Uruguayans could say that
it is the worst place of the...

06:57.106 --> 06:58.935
Well, a lot of it...
That's weird.

06:58.970 --> 07:00.937
Some of the Uruguayans
I've spoken to

07:00.972 --> 07:03.112
are very ambivalent...
Yeah.

07:03.146 --> 07:06.149
- About your country.
- "I like it, but you know..."

07:06.184 --> 07:07.772
And this I don't
really understand.

07:09.325 --> 07:12.639
I meet Carina Novarese,
a journalist and editor

07:12.673 --> 07:14.951
with the newspaper
"El Observador"

07:14.986 --> 07:18.023
at Escaramuza
Cafe and Bookstore.

07:18.058 --> 07:20.923
I think this thing
that Uruguayan has

07:20.957 --> 07:22.614
that is kind of pessimistic

07:22.649 --> 07:24.057
and is always...
Sometimes complains too much

07:24.064 --> 07:27.308
about what we have
comes from before.

07:27.343 --> 07:31.278
1930s, '40s, and
after the Second World War,

07:31.312 --> 07:33.798
this was one of the Americas
as they used to call us.

07:33.832 --> 07:37.387
There are few reminders of
colonial days in Montevideo,

07:37.422 --> 07:40.943
but plenty of evidence
that this is the chief city

07:40.977 --> 07:43.842
of a dynamic
and progressive country.

07:43.877 --> 07:46.396
It was a pretty cool society.

07:46.431 --> 07:49.123
Healthcare was free,
cradle-to-grave.

07:49.158 --> 07:53.196
Uh, education free.
Also a very big medium class.

07:53.231 --> 07:54.888
That is very important
for Uruguay.

07:54.922 --> 07:56.372
- Right.
- That began to change

07:56.406 --> 07:58.339
after the '60s and '70s.

07:58.374 --> 08:00.549
One could say that
the prospect of

08:00.583 --> 08:02.516
socialist, or God forbid,
communist movements

08:02.551 --> 08:04.484
in Latin America in the '60s

08:04.518 --> 08:07.383
was an area
of great concern for the U.S.

08:07.417 --> 08:09.143
and its more
authoritarian-leaning

08:09.178 --> 08:11.180
allies in the region.

08:11.214 --> 08:14.252
So the emergence of the radical
National Liberation Movement,

08:14.286 --> 08:18.532
known as the Tupamaros, was
cause for alarm at the CIA.

08:18.567 --> 08:20.672
A lot of things happened
in the '60s

08:20.707 --> 08:22.363
in the context of Latin America.

08:22.398 --> 08:25.021
A lot of students, young people,

08:25.056 --> 08:27.817
were very active in politics.

08:27.852 --> 08:30.199
There weren't the low classes,
as you could say.

08:30.233 --> 08:32.056
They weren't the poor people
who were doing this.

08:32.063 --> 08:34.058
These are middle-class kids
and highly radicalized.

08:34.065 --> 08:35.445
Yeah.
At the beginning, I think,

08:35.480 --> 08:38.414
they really thought
they could change the system.

08:38.448 --> 08:41.417
With covert and overt
support by our country,

08:41.451 --> 08:43.557
a state of emergency
was declared,

08:43.592 --> 08:45.041
and a right-wing dictatorship

08:45.076 --> 08:47.250
grabbed hold of
the instruments of power

08:47.285 --> 08:49.563
launching a period of
repression that

08:49.598 --> 08:53.256
lasted from 1973 until 1985.

08:53.291 --> 08:56.536
Supported and often
guided by CIA officers

08:56.570 --> 08:58.468
trained in
what we call these days

08:58.503 --> 09:00.919
"enhanced
interrogation methods,"

09:00.954 --> 09:02.887
some of the most brutal bastards

09:02.921 --> 09:05.234
in the ugliest
military juntas on Earth

09:05.268 --> 09:09.410
crushed minds and bodies
in cells across Latin America.

09:09.445 --> 09:11.758
What kind of people were
finding themselves swept up?

09:11.792 --> 09:13.483
- Especially teachers.
- Teachers?

09:13.518 --> 09:16.797
- Professors from university.
- Troublesome intellectuals.

09:16.832 --> 09:18.592
Sometimes lawyers or...

09:18.627 --> 09:22.078
Something like 3% to 5%
of the entire population,

09:22.113 --> 09:25.254
uh, had gone through
the prison system.

09:25.288 --> 09:27.290
I mean, we're not talking
about incarceration.

09:27.325 --> 09:28.630
We're talking about...
No, no, no, no.

09:28.637 --> 09:29.983
They were tortured and then

09:30.017 --> 09:31.709
kept inside a prison system

09:31.743 --> 09:35.816
that was specifically designed
to pretty much destroy them.

09:35.851 --> 09:40.165
In the mid 1980s, the people
of Uruguay had had enough.

09:40.200 --> 09:42.478
Massive demonstrations
and strikes finally

09:42.512 --> 09:45.136
forced the government
to hold elections,

09:45.170 --> 09:47.276
and the military
was swept from power.

09:47.310 --> 09:49.968
We're now a democratic country
since 1984.

09:50.003 --> 09:52.764
- And how's it going?
- I think it's going well.

09:52.799 --> 09:56.009
We have troubles.
We are in Latin America.

09:56.043 --> 09:58.943
We'd like to believe that
we are a European country.

09:58.977 --> 10:00.358
We are not.

10:00.392 --> 10:02.774
- But are you optimistic?
- I am.

10:02.809 --> 10:04.189
I am.

10:04.224 --> 10:08.469
I don't see, like,
a huge crisis coming.

10:08.504 --> 10:13.095
But also when they came,
you never realized before too.

10:13.129 --> 10:13.629
♪

10:29.594 --> 10:31.182
♪

10:31.216 --> 10:32.528
When people think of this

10:32.562 --> 10:34.392
often overlooked little country,

10:34.426 --> 10:37.153
if they think of it at all,
they tend to think of it

10:37.188 --> 10:40.329
patronizingly as
Argentina's little brother.

10:40.363 --> 10:41.641
Not so.

10:41.675 --> 10:43.470
And that attitude
pushes people here

10:43.504 --> 10:45.334
to think of themselves
in many ways

10:45.368 --> 10:47.785
as existentially in opposition

10:47.819 --> 10:50.063
to their
bigger, louder neighbor.

10:50.097 --> 10:51.996
Where were you born?
Are you from Montevideo?

10:52.030 --> 10:54.067
No, no, I'm from Argentina.

10:54.101 --> 10:55.689
Is it a big difference
culturally,

10:55.724 --> 10:57.346
Argentina and Uruguay?

10:57.380 --> 10:59.797
Here, if you're
a little bit courageous,

10:59.831 --> 11:02.144
then you made it, you know?
It's a scene here.

11:02.178 --> 11:04.215
Like, to be flashy,
it... it's a scene.

11:04.249 --> 11:07.321
To be successful, it's not
something that is one scene.

11:07.356 --> 11:09.013
You got to do it quietly.

11:09.047 --> 11:11.153
There's a saying,
"[speaking Spanish]."

11:11.187 --> 11:13.258
It means "Stay in
the small thing," you know?

11:13.293 --> 11:15.157
Right..

11:15.191 --> 11:16.710
It's something that defines...
Right.

11:16.745 --> 11:19.437
Uruguay in a way.

11:19.471 --> 11:23.234
Lucia Soria is the
chef and owner of Jacinto

11:23.268 --> 11:25.443
in Montevideo's old city.

11:25.477 --> 11:28.722
She worked with Nacho
back in the Mallmann years.

11:28.757 --> 11:30.620
What was it like for a woman

11:30.655 --> 11:35.556
working in the restaurant
industry in the early 2000s?

11:35.591 --> 11:39.043
I was very lucky
because Francis, he had, like,

11:39.077 --> 11:42.115
this army of women... no?
Around him.

11:42.149 --> 11:44.393
You were surrounded by women
from the beginning?

11:44.427 --> 11:45.774
Yes. Yes.

11:45.808 --> 11:48.362
Is that an unusual situation
in Uruguay do you think?

11:48.397 --> 11:50.882
- I mean...
- I'm not asking you, man.

11:50.917 --> 11:52.290
You're... you're a man.
I'm asking...

11:52.297 --> 11:55.749
Oh, I sound like a woman.

11:55.784 --> 11:59.373
The food here takes its cues
from Spain and Italy.

11:59.408 --> 12:02.445
Homemade gnocchi
with mushrooms and pumpkin.

12:02.480 --> 12:06.380
Prawns with avocado,
apple, and wasabi.

12:06.415 --> 12:10.281
Beef tartare with quail egg.

12:10.315 --> 12:13.284
So when you were first
planning the menu for this place

12:13.318 --> 12:14.941
and thinking about the
concept...

12:14.975 --> 12:16.666
- Yeah.
- What inspired you?

12:16.701 --> 12:18.876
I wanted to have, like,
a small restaurant,

12:18.910 --> 12:21.430
but that you could have
a very nice everything,

12:21.464 --> 12:24.295
but small, you know?
You want fish?

12:24.329 --> 12:27.470
Very nice and a little
vegetables, you know?

12:27.505 --> 12:29.334
Right.
This is the most vegetables

12:29.369 --> 12:31.889
I've ever seen in this country
all in one time.

12:31.923 --> 12:33.407
We're all driven people

12:33.442 --> 12:35.271
at this table.
Yeah.

12:35.306 --> 12:36.714
You know, you went
all the way to New York.

12:36.721 --> 12:37.991
You have how many restaurants
in New York now?

12:37.998 --> 12:38.992
Just the one? Two?
Three.

12:38.999 --> 12:40.414
- Three.
- Three.

12:40.449 --> 12:41.684
- Nice number, man.
- You're not lazy.

12:41.691 --> 12:42.858
- No.
- It's just a little dump.

12:42.865 --> 12:44.108
You could have seven.

12:44.142 --> 12:45.626
I'm gonna guess
you're like this too.

12:45.661 --> 12:48.181
We're all driven people,
so where is your happy place?

12:48.215 --> 12:50.942
Well, I got married
on Saturday, and...

12:50.977 --> 12:53.117
- This past Saturday?
- Yes.

12:53.151 --> 12:57.673
That was the day that
I felt happy all day.

12:57.707 --> 13:02.022
But it's good because you cannot
have happiness all the time, no?

13:02.057 --> 13:03.292
Happiness is a thing that...
No, no.

13:03.299 --> 13:04.818
Happiness all the time
is fascism.

13:04.853 --> 13:06.468
- No. It doesn't exist, man.
- It's oppressive.

13:06.475 --> 13:08.304
It's oppressive.
You're not doing anything.

13:08.339 --> 13:11.514
But if you have
a few moments a week,

13:11.549 --> 13:14.448
will you just go,
"Oh, shit. I'm happy"?

13:14.483 --> 13:16.140
- Yeah.
- It sneaks up on you.

13:19.177 --> 13:19.677
♪

13:24.079 --> 13:26.184
Which is more satisfying,

13:26.219 --> 13:27.979
eating a good meal...
Yeah.

13:28.014 --> 13:29.360
Or cooking a good meal

13:29.394 --> 13:32.846
for somebody
you really care about?

13:32.881 --> 13:34.399
I think eating.

13:34.434 --> 13:36.885
I... I actually enjoy both,

13:36.919 --> 13:38.300
but I don't want
to hear anything.

13:38.334 --> 13:39.680
I don't want you to talk to me.

13:39.715 --> 13:41.192
I just want to see
your expression, like,

13:41.199 --> 13:42.683
seeing you're connecting

13:42.718 --> 13:44.996
without having to
have a dialogue about it.

13:45.031 --> 13:46.653
I'm not sure.

13:46.687 --> 13:48.689
Cooking for customers,
that's a different experience.

13:48.724 --> 13:52.486
Making an omelet for someone...
Mm.

13:52.521 --> 13:56.007
The morning after.
Just stay in.

13:56.042 --> 13:58.872
Yeah.
It's really the best.

13:58.907 --> 14:01.185
The guy that I marry,

14:01.219 --> 14:03.601
I was with him
for the first time.

14:03.635 --> 14:06.776
And I cooked three eggs,
two asparagus,

14:06.811 --> 14:10.573
and five cherry tomatoes
with my heart.

14:10.608 --> 14:14.198
And we had this small
but very beautiful

14:14.232 --> 14:17.373
breakfast, brunch, lunch.

14:17.408 --> 14:19.444
It's the best thing ever.
You're gonna make me cry.

14:19.479 --> 14:21.239
- You know?
- You're gonna make me cry.

14:21.274 --> 14:24.035
There's some basic urge
that made

14:24.070 --> 14:26.244
all of us at this table
want to cook.

14:26.279 --> 14:28.626
- Yeah.
- There is a desire to

14:28.660 --> 14:30.904
say something you can't say,
to nurture.

14:30.939 --> 14:34.218
So basic, and it's so
beautiful that it's so basic.

14:34.252 --> 14:34.752
♪

14:45.746 --> 14:46.246
♪

15:06.940 --> 15:10.392
Hablan por la Espalda
got together in 1996

15:10.426 --> 15:12.428
when they were all
just teenagers.

15:12.463 --> 15:13.843
They were considered pioneers

15:13.878 --> 15:16.467
of the DIY
hardcore movement here.

15:16.501 --> 15:18.434
Two decades on,
they're still one of

15:18.469 --> 15:20.402
the country's
most popular bands.

15:20.436 --> 15:23.681
And they recently opened
for Iggy Pop.

15:23.715 --> 15:27.478
♪

15:36.694 --> 15:38.938
Right, so what does everybody
do here? What do you do?

15:38.972 --> 15:40.801
- I'm psychologist.
- You're a psychologist?

15:40.836 --> 15:43.666
This will come in useful later.

15:43.701 --> 15:46.462
Musician and a...
I'm a writer too.

15:46.497 --> 15:49.293
- Writer and, uh, restaurateur.
- Yeah.

15:49.327 --> 15:51.295
I work in post production.

15:51.329 --> 15:52.952
- Post production?
- Yeah.

15:52.986 --> 15:55.713
That could be... actually this
is a very useful table.

15:58.509 --> 16:00.994
Fermin, the lead
singer and songwriter,

16:01.029 --> 16:02.168
grew up with Nacho.

16:02.202 --> 16:04.998
Tuca and Valentin play guitar.

16:05.033 --> 16:07.138
What do people like
to listen to in Uruguay?

16:07.173 --> 16:08.726
It's a very musical country,
I think.

16:08.760 --> 16:10.866
You know Candombe?
Yeah.

16:10.900 --> 16:14.007
Okay, that's our, like,
our native rhythm.

16:14.042 --> 16:17.493
And the folklore from here,
it used to be called...

16:17.528 --> 16:18.832
"protest music..."
Protest music.

16:18.839 --> 16:22.153
So it was, like,
late '60s, early '70s,

16:22.188 --> 16:23.879
was the most popular music.

16:23.913 --> 16:26.295
But then came the dictatorship.
Right, so no more of that.

16:26.330 --> 16:28.504
And everybody
had to leave the country.

16:28.539 --> 16:29.919
Yeah, dictatorships are usually,

16:29.954 --> 16:32.370
like, usually bad for music.
Yeah.

16:32.405 --> 16:34.055
They're good for
the underground music scene,

16:34.062 --> 16:35.056
but not so good for the...

16:35.063 --> 16:36.167
Not for the popular music.

16:39.550 --> 16:41.034
Do you want to smoke?
Yeah, sure.

16:41.069 --> 16:43.347
- I brought some.
- Excellent. Good idea.

16:43.381 --> 16:45.901
I... I am permitted
to smoke weed on camera now.

16:45.935 --> 16:49.422
- Yeah. You are in Uruguay.
- I am observing local custom.

16:49.456 --> 16:52.563
♪

16:52.597 --> 16:54.599
Proceed to smoke weed.

16:54.634 --> 16:56.774
It's cool.
Everybody's doing it.

16:56.808 --> 16:58.672
Somebody call
the elfin Jeff Sessions.

16:58.707 --> 17:00.053
He'll shit himself.

17:00.088 --> 17:01.537
How long
has weed been legal here?

17:01.572 --> 17:02.780
- One year.
- A year?

17:02.814 --> 17:04.575
- One year, yeah.
- A year? Awesome.

17:04.608 --> 17:07.060
But here, like, you could
smoke in the street...

17:07.095 --> 17:08.199
- Always.
- For always.

17:08.233 --> 17:09.545
Do you have dispensaries?

17:09.579 --> 17:10.815
Do you have stores
that you can go through?

17:10.821 --> 17:12.238
Yes, that's the problem
here now.

17:12.271 --> 17:13.749
The pharmacies cannot sell
because the...

17:13.756 --> 17:15.550
- The international banks...
- Right.

17:15.586 --> 17:17.519
Don't want to accept drug money.

17:17.553 --> 17:20.935
So if I were to open
a marijuana hydroponic farm...

17:20.970 --> 17:22.386
You can have your club.

17:22.420 --> 17:24.181
All right, when...
When we starting this?

17:24.214 --> 17:25.560
I don't know, man.

17:25.596 --> 17:27.287
Let me smoke another joint.

17:27.321 --> 17:28.288
There, you got it.

17:31.464 --> 17:31.964
♪

17:41.439 --> 17:41.939
♪

17:51.449 --> 17:52.933
What to do next?

17:52.968 --> 17:56.799
Pizza and beers, yo,
at Bar Las Flores.

17:56.834 --> 17:59.457
So, uh, here's
an interesting question.

17:59.492 --> 18:03.427
What is the national
pathology of Uruguay?

18:03.461 --> 18:05.981
- It is the envy from...
- Envy?

18:06.015 --> 18:08.949
Yes, Uruguayan very envy.

18:08.984 --> 18:11.573
You always envy, like...

18:11.607 --> 18:15.404
I cannot envy a very
big guitarist, guitar player.

18:15.439 --> 18:17.993
I cannot envy Paco de Lucia.

18:18.027 --> 18:20.651
I will envy
this kind of guitarist

18:20.685 --> 18:22.929
that plays almost like me,
just a little better.

18:22.963 --> 18:24.965
- Just a little better.
- Just a little better.

18:28.383 --> 18:29.453
Yeah.

18:29.487 --> 18:31.972
The envy is between brothers.

18:32.007 --> 18:34.147
Right.
Is this a destructive envy?

18:34.182 --> 18:37.702
Do Uruguayans want
other Uruguayans to succeed?

18:37.737 --> 18:39.670
- As long as they're far enough.
- Yeah.

18:39.704 --> 18:42.811
Not my neighbor.
Not in my neighborhood.

18:42.845 --> 18:44.675
This is an honest man.
I really like you.

18:44.709 --> 18:46.953
I love this Uruguayan.
He's in Mexico. He's great.

18:46.987 --> 18:48.989
I feel like
I'm talking to myself.

18:53.028 --> 18:54.512
♪

18:54.547 --> 18:57.550
The pizza here is
a bizarro stoner hybrid

18:57.584 --> 18:59.828
topped with
thin chickpea flatbread.

18:59.862 --> 19:02.210
Why?
I don't know.

19:02.244 --> 19:03.659
Makes sense though.

19:03.694 --> 19:05.627
The one on top of there
is a fainá.

19:05.661 --> 19:09.182
You should put fainá
on top of the pizza.

19:09.217 --> 19:11.011
Really?

19:11.046 --> 19:11.546
♪

19:17.742 --> 19:20.055
We call this pizza
no cheese now.

19:20.089 --> 19:23.196
- Yeah.
- He's a vegan, so he's...

19:23.231 --> 19:24.197
Really?

19:26.095 --> 19:27.511
I don't know
if I can work with you.

19:27.545 --> 19:28.719
22 years, I'm vegan.

19:28.753 --> 19:30.410
- Vegan?
- Yes, in Uruguay.

19:30.445 --> 19:32.585
Wow, that is
a revolutionary position.

19:32.619 --> 19:34.552
They used to be vegan too.

19:34.587 --> 19:36.209
- Yeah.
- You are such an asshole.

19:37.624 --> 19:39.212
He used to be
very vegan militant.

19:39.247 --> 19:40.593
So what did you eat?

19:40.627 --> 19:43.112
- Pizza.
- Yeah, but no cheese?

19:43.147 --> 19:44.838
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

19:44.873 --> 19:48.704
And this is on health grounds,
or you hate to herd animals?

19:48.739 --> 19:50.430
I don't know.

19:50.465 --> 19:52.432
Okay, if you had to kill
Fred Durst or a cow?

19:52.467 --> 19:53.571
- Oh...
- Or a cow.

19:53.606 --> 19:54.848
Fred. Fred.

19:56.574 --> 19:59.059
Look, this one.
Iggy Pop or a cow?

19:59.094 --> 20:00.233
I like Iggy Pop,

20:00.268 --> 20:02.373
but I will have to kill him.

20:02.408 --> 20:04.341
- No?
- No!

20:04.375 --> 20:06.964
No.

20:06.998 --> 20:08.586
Oh, no.

20:08.621 --> 20:11.348
- I just saw him live.
- You're a monster.

20:11.382 --> 20:13.695
You are not my therapist.

20:17.181 --> 20:17.681
♪

20:30.746 --> 20:33.473
♪

21:09.302 --> 21:09.802
♪

22:07.912 --> 22:09.638
All right, meat.
I want meat.

22:09.673 --> 22:10.701
And this is the place.
You want meat?

22:10.708 --> 22:12.469
Yes.
Yes, I do.

22:12.503 --> 22:15.472
This must be the place.

22:15.506 --> 22:18.371
His friends say
Marcello Quiben looks German,

22:18.406 --> 22:20.891
hence the name of his
small neighborhood restaurant

22:20.925 --> 22:23.514
"Parisa el Aleman."

22:23.549 --> 22:26.862
The beating heart of the place
is, of course, the Parisa,

22:26.897 --> 22:29.486
a grill where
dripping meats of many kinds

22:29.520 --> 22:32.385
are slowly cooked
over glowing wood coals.

22:32.420 --> 22:34.698
Why is this an Uruguayan thing? Why here?

22:34.732 --> 22:37.010
I mean, I know
you're a cattle country.

22:37.045 --> 22:39.254
I think the first settlers,
when they came in,

22:39.288 --> 22:42.050
they realized there was nothing
else but raising cattle.

22:42.084 --> 22:43.845
- Right.
- And they let it grow wild.

22:43.879 --> 22:45.916
- Uh-huh.
- And they over-populated.

22:45.950 --> 22:49.575
And, you know, gauchos,
they would roam the land,

22:49.609 --> 22:54.027
and they would kill it on
the spot and actually cook it...

22:54.062 --> 22:55.574
- Right there.
- ...right there on the spot.

22:55.581 --> 22:58.549
And actually, like, a lot of
times with the skin on.

22:58.584 --> 23:01.552
Really?

23:01.587 --> 23:04.417
Morcilla, or blood sausage.

23:04.452 --> 23:07.593
Oh, now this is what
it's all about for me now.

23:07.627 --> 23:09.422
Every great culture does this.

23:09.457 --> 23:11.148
It's moist.
I love it.

23:11.182 --> 23:14.082
Right when you kill it,
it's pretty amazing.

23:14.116 --> 23:16.705
Look, when they kill me,
that's the way I want to go.

23:16.740 --> 23:17.837
You know,
keep the heart beating,

23:17.844 --> 23:19.225
pump the blood into the bucket,

23:19.259 --> 23:22.573
let the village women
come and make sausage.

23:22.608 --> 23:23.747
Then chorizo.

23:23.781 --> 23:25.990
Then steak... gotta have that.

23:26.025 --> 23:29.131
In this case, rib eye.

23:29.166 --> 23:31.444
You should spend more time
in this country.

23:31.479 --> 23:34.585
I don't know.
I've been gone for 17, 18 years.

23:34.620 --> 23:35.897
Yeah.

23:35.931 --> 23:37.554
It feels kind of like the same.

23:37.588 --> 23:39.279
That's the magic
about this place.

23:39.314 --> 23:40.964
It's like, it feels like
traveling into the past.

23:40.971 --> 23:43.111
I don't see Starbucks
on every corner.

23:43.145 --> 23:46.079
I don't see McDonald's.
It's sort of unspoiled, right?

23:46.114 --> 23:48.143
This is pretty awesome.
I mean, am I missing something?

23:48.150 --> 23:50.463
Is there something that
really sucks about this country

23:50.498 --> 23:52.189
that I don't... I've not seen?

23:52.223 --> 23:55.503
I think this... it's a society
that's, like, very patriarchal.

23:55.537 --> 23:57.366
Ah.

23:57.401 --> 24:01.509
And it has a lot of colonial
tradition that overshadows...

24:01.543 --> 24:04.201
Yeah, but compared to what?
Compared to who?

24:04.235 --> 24:06.514
Who's doing really great
in that department?

24:06.548 --> 24:07.825
Denmark?

24:07.860 --> 24:10.172
It's, like, the happiest
country on Earth.

24:10.207 --> 24:12.381
I hate happy.

24:12.416 --> 24:14.342
I mean, you want to be
surrounded by happy people?

24:14.349 --> 24:18.629
Do you notice how melancholic
this place is and nostalgic?

24:18.664 --> 24:20.148
It's like
you walk on the street,

24:20.182 --> 24:22.219
and you just, like, feel it.
Yeah.

24:22.253 --> 24:24.773
It's, like,
the melancholy, it's...

24:24.808 --> 24:26.154
I like that.

24:29.364 --> 24:29.864
♪

24:39.685 --> 24:41.410
Nacho Mattos grew up

24:41.445 --> 24:43.654
about 45 minutes
north of the capital

24:43.689 --> 24:47.175
in Santa Lucia,
a small town of 16,000 people

24:47.209 --> 24:51.731
surrounded by farmland
and cattle and sheep ranches.

24:51.766 --> 24:56.391
I think as a child, it was
an incredible place to grow up.

24:56.425 --> 24:59.325
You know, I like escaping and
going fishing on the river,

24:59.359 --> 25:01.879
and that's pretty safe,
you know?

25:01.914 --> 25:04.986
Like, the doors
were always open.

25:05.020 --> 25:08.507
But I didn't feel like
I fit in at all.

25:10.301 --> 25:15.548
And I needed to find a place
and a way to express myself.

25:15.583 --> 25:17.343
We were raised as very liberal,

25:17.377 --> 25:20.933
but at the same time,
it's conservative.

25:20.967 --> 25:24.281
As a teenager, it was kind of
like everything the same.

25:24.315 --> 25:26.697
It's just, you didn't
feel that interesting.

25:26.732 --> 25:29.873
And yeah,
it wasn't fun as a teenager.

25:29.907 --> 25:32.461
♪

25:32.496 --> 25:35.430
His family own a dairy farm
just outside of town.

25:35.464 --> 25:37.915
Nacho's mother, Gloria,
runs the farm

25:37.950 --> 25:40.297
along with his brother, Leandro.

25:40.331 --> 25:42.713
Nacho's sister, Rocio,
lives in Montevideo

25:42.748 --> 25:46.717
but comes home often
for family meals like this.

25:46.752 --> 25:48.609
What's the name of this town?
You grew up here? This house?

25:48.616 --> 25:50.403
- Santa Lucia. Yeah.
- You grew up in this house?

25:50.410 --> 25:52.412
Yes.
For the most part, yeah.

25:52.447 --> 25:54.932
It's beautiful. Why
would you ever leave this place?

25:54.967 --> 25:56.934
It's fantastic.
He never liked this place.

25:56.969 --> 25:58.142
- No?
- No, never.

25:58.177 --> 26:00.075
I felt like he had, like,

26:00.110 --> 26:04.079
anger of being
on such a small town.

26:04.114 --> 26:06.461
He always had, like,
been on the front.

26:06.495 --> 26:09.878
I couldn't fit in here,
so I get out of the house,

26:09.913 --> 26:11.431
and I actually call her

26:11.466 --> 26:13.116
and say that I wanted
to go to culinary school.

26:13.123 --> 26:14.711
"This is what I want to do.

26:14.745 --> 26:16.298
I need support,
and I pay you back."

26:16.333 --> 26:20.924
And one year goes, and
I drop it to work for Francis.

26:20.958 --> 26:23.236
I... I love that you went
from being a vegan to

26:23.271 --> 26:24.783
working with Francis Mallmann...
Yeah, yeah.

26:24.790 --> 26:27.482
...who's, like, you know,
the Satan of vegans.

26:27.516 --> 26:29.588
What was at the dinner table
when you grew up?

26:29.622 --> 26:32.452
Mom wasn't that... it wasn't
that skillful in the kitchen.

26:32.487 --> 26:34.765
- Oh, that's cold, man.
- I know, but it is true.

26:34.800 --> 26:36.146
She was the one in charge.

26:36.180 --> 26:37.941
So you grew up eating
a lot of Italian food?

26:37.975 --> 26:40.357
Yes.

26:40.391 --> 26:43.602
Nacho's grandmother,
Ercilia, was born here,

26:43.636 --> 26:46.294
the child of Italian immigrants.

26:46.328 --> 26:48.123
I grew up around my grandmother,

26:48.158 --> 26:50.954
like, constantly cooking.

26:50.988 --> 26:53.784
And that was her form
of affection

26:53.819 --> 26:56.097
and a way of, like,

26:56.131 --> 26:58.651
showing that she cared
and she love you.

27:04.692 --> 27:05.192
♪

27:12.078 --> 27:14.460
Her tucco, her version
of Sunday gravy,

27:14.494 --> 27:17.187
is made from porchetta,
cured pork ribs,

27:17.221 --> 27:20.224
and hunks of beef
simmered for hours.

27:30.683 --> 27:32.305
There's also matambre,

27:32.340 --> 27:34.894
a local specialty
of rolled stuffed beef

27:34.929 --> 27:38.691
served alongside Russian salad.

27:38.726 --> 27:40.348
So when did you start cooking?

27:40.382 --> 27:43.972
I think... I think it was,
like, my mom get divorced,

27:44.007 --> 27:46.009
and I realized
that she needed help,

27:46.043 --> 27:49.840
and I start cooking
as a way of support.

27:49.875 --> 27:52.532
- Mm-hmm.
- Then I decide to become vegan,

27:52.567 --> 27:54.707
and she was like...
She threw the towel.

27:54.742 --> 27:57.848
And I was like... and
and she stopped cooking for us.

27:57.883 --> 28:00.989
So I start taking the
initiative, and I start cooking.

28:01.024 --> 28:02.266
Well, you had to because

28:02.301 --> 28:04.544
you were the only vegan
in all of Uruguay.

28:09.480 --> 28:09.980
♪

28:13.761 --> 28:15.383
How often does he come back?

28:15.417 --> 28:17.109
- Two years?
- It's been two years?

28:17.143 --> 28:19.214
- Mm-hmm.
- I like it. I like it.

28:19.249 --> 28:22.873
I like it in a different way.
I like it far away.

28:24.426 --> 28:28.741
If he would find
the thing to do here,

28:28.776 --> 28:30.294
like, he would be happy,

28:30.329 --> 28:34.057
but the things he wants to do
are not here.

28:34.091 --> 28:36.059
♪

28:38.268 --> 28:39.925
Si?
Yeah, it's good.

28:39.959 --> 28:42.721
- It's so comforting.
- Yeah.

28:42.755 --> 28:44.136
This makes me happy.

28:44.170 --> 28:44.670
♪

29:06.641 --> 29:09.092
♪

29:18.170 --> 29:21.345
♪

29:41.193 --> 29:43.609
Fishing from kayaks
is... is amazing.

29:43.643 --> 29:45.369
First of all,
it's easy, really easy.

29:45.404 --> 29:47.544
You don't need
any motor or nothing.

29:47.578 --> 29:50.098
It's just bring the kayak
to the shore

29:50.133 --> 29:51.651
and paddle in.

29:51.686 --> 29:52.186
♪

30:44.394 --> 30:47.846
A couple of hours east
of Montevideo, the coast,

30:47.880 --> 30:50.227
and the seaside towns
of high-gloss,

30:50.262 --> 30:52.402
big money, Punta del Este,

30:52.436 --> 30:55.336
and the slightly more
laid back Jose Ignacio,

30:55.370 --> 30:57.165
once a sleepy fishing village,

30:57.200 --> 30:59.374
and now a Hamptonian
vacation hotspot

30:59.409 --> 31:02.584
for the money class
from all over the world.

31:02.619 --> 31:03.119
♪

31:09.108 --> 31:13.216
Cantina del Vigia, thankfully,
is open in the off season.

31:13.250 --> 31:17.289
Diego Robino is a film producer
and occasional fisherman,

31:17.323 --> 31:19.878
and Clo Dimet
is a chef and owner of

31:19.912 --> 31:22.604
a posada in Jose Ignacio.

31:22.639 --> 31:24.089
So what town is this?
Where am I?

31:24.123 --> 31:25.884
- This is Maldonado.
- Maldonado.

31:25.918 --> 31:29.818
And this is, like, the capital
of all these fancy beach towns,

31:29.853 --> 31:31.717
but this is where
the working class people live.

31:31.751 --> 31:34.409
It's the city where
most people live all the year.

31:34.444 --> 31:37.550
Cantina's chef/owner
is Federico Desseno.

31:37.585 --> 31:40.588
Like Nacho, another
Francis Mallmann veteran.

31:40.622 --> 31:43.936
Diego brought some fish
he caught today.

31:43.971 --> 31:47.906
We got empanadas with corn
and shredded slow-cooked beef.

31:47.940 --> 31:49.459
Ooh, nice.
Love it.

31:49.493 --> 31:51.081
Oh, I'm liking
this meal already.

31:51.116 --> 31:53.912
There's goat cheese
and spinach croquettes.

31:55.465 --> 31:56.915
- Mmm.
- Nice.

31:56.949 --> 31:58.951
- Look at the catch.
- Oh, look at that.

31:58.986 --> 32:01.678
- This is the catch of the day.
- Beautiful.

32:01.712 --> 32:03.576
♪

32:03.611 --> 32:07.960
So today Diego went
on one of the roughest day

32:07.995 --> 32:11.101
in the ocean
to get fish somehow.

32:11.136 --> 32:12.654
We're talking about,
like, hard work.

32:12.689 --> 32:14.967
I mean, the kitchen is hard,
but like, fishermen...

32:15.002 --> 32:17.625
No, the fact that you are
alone in the middle of the ocean

32:17.659 --> 32:20.766
with all this
destruction around you...

32:20.800 --> 32:23.286
That's why we play soccer.

32:26.841 --> 32:29.602
There are
two wood-fired ovens producing

32:29.637 --> 32:34.435
this thing, provoleta,
a beautiful slab of cheese

32:34.469 --> 32:37.645
which puffs up and
inflates in the heat.

32:37.679 --> 32:40.303
Wow.

32:40.337 --> 32:41.649
Whoa, and this is the cheese?

32:41.683 --> 32:43.271
The history...
This is the cheese.

32:43.306 --> 32:45.653
Normally if you're doing
a grill with friends,

32:45.687 --> 32:50.037
this is the only thing
you will get that is not meat.

32:50.071 --> 32:52.901
Whole-roasted suckling
wild boar.

32:52.936 --> 32:53.436
♪

32:57.423 --> 32:59.529
Wow, that's spectacular.

32:59.563 --> 33:01.462
And whole-roasted fish.

33:01.496 --> 33:01.996
♪

33:06.053 --> 33:07.019
- Whoa.
- Fish.

33:07.054 --> 33:08.365
- Fish.
- Wow.

33:13.543 --> 33:15.510
And milanesa.

33:15.545 --> 33:17.823
Here in Uruguay,
not veal as in Italy,

33:17.857 --> 33:20.929
but a pounded, breaded,
and fried hunk of beef

33:20.964 --> 33:26.142
covered in tomato sauce, ham,
and melted mozzarella cheese.

33:26.176 --> 33:27.350
Oh, more cheese.
All right.

33:27.384 --> 33:28.696
Milanesa.

33:28.730 --> 33:30.422
This is milanesa napolitana.

33:30.456 --> 33:31.871
- Right.
- And it's a typical dish.

33:31.906 --> 33:34.357
And the people here
eat a lot of milanesa.

33:34.391 --> 33:37.049
- We grew up with this.
- All the people.

33:37.084 --> 33:38.499
Holy moley.

33:38.533 --> 33:40.708
Yeah, you know this is
good cold, too, right?

33:40.742 --> 33:42.054
First thing in the morning?

33:42.089 --> 33:43.883
Cold?
It's great.

33:43.918 --> 33:45.885
See, you have an instinctive
sense in this country

33:45.920 --> 33:48.026
of what people need.

33:48.060 --> 33:48.560
♪

34:01.798 --> 34:02.298
♪

34:17.676 --> 34:20.368
How much you loving Uruguay?

34:20.402 --> 34:21.914
You still loving it,
or you change your mind?

34:21.920 --> 34:24.407
I love it.
It's beautiful, so laid back.

34:24.440 --> 34:25.614
You haven't changed that...

34:25.649 --> 34:27.203
Your mind a little bit?
No.

34:27.237 --> 34:29.239
Feel tense about anything,
I smoke a little weed.

34:29.274 --> 34:33.416
I feel better.

34:33.449 --> 34:37.282
Yeah?
I'm getting hungry actually.

34:37.315 --> 34:38.835
Yeah, what's
on the menu tonight?

34:38.869 --> 34:40.284
Got some quinoa?
Maybe some quinoa.

34:40.319 --> 34:41.589
I don't think
it exists, quinoa, here.

34:41.596 --> 34:42.969
You might see it
in some health store.

